Editing Wordlists:
 
  The wordlists may be edited,  or new ones created,  with or without the
Handirom active.
 
  To do this,  type CHAIN"EDIT" or CH."EDIT" followed by RETURN (you must
be in BASIC to do this).
 
  The editor is easy to use and prompts the user firstly for the filename
of  the wordlist to edit or RETURN for a new wordlist.  The wordlists are
all kept  in  directory  W but there is no need to specify this directory
with.
 
  Try loading STDWORD then add  and  delete words to familiarise yourself
with the editor.  Using the F)inish option will prompt for a filename.
 
  Do not use the original filename or you run the risk of corrupting your
data (assuming that the file is not locked).
 
Limitations:
 
  Handirom  will NOT work with the Inter Word wordprocessor,  Acornsoft's
Basic Editor or any basic program using INKEY(n).  It is also unlikely to
work with programs or roms which use text or graphics windows.
 
  A further  limitation  is  that  the  cursor  editing  and copying keys
produce   unpredictable  results  in  the  command  type  of  environment
i.e.  where  a  "*"  command  may  be  issued.  The best way to return to
normal  operation  after an anomaly has occurred is to  press  escape  or
return from the keyboard.
 
  When using a  wordprocessor  such  as  View  3.0,   which  obeys window
definitions  on  startup,   it  is  necessary to have the Handirom active
before entering the command *WORD and  to  issue  the *WORD command after
each change of screen mode (within View,  of course).
 
  Although  the  Handirom  is compatible with the BBC micro or the Master
with or without the  6502  Tube,   the  Tube  itself must be switched off
before attempting to load into sideways ram.  Once loaded,   the Tube may
be switched on and a CTRL-BREAK issued to initialise it.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
